## Summary

- Problem: Telegram replies ending with `notify=false` leaked the marker into the visible message body instead of silencing the notification, as reported in #80569.
- Solution: Detect and strip a trailing `\n+notify\s*=\s*false\s*$` pattern (case-insensitive) in `deliverReplies`, and forward `disable_notification: true` to the Telegram Bot API so the message is delivered silently.
- What changed: `extensions/telegram/src/bot/delivery.replies.ts` (+24/−1): added `hasTrailingNotifyFalse` / `stripTrailingNotifyFalse` helpers and integrated into `deliverReplies`. `extensions/telegram/src/bot/delivery.test.ts` (+31/−0): two regression tests.
- What did NOT change: No changes to shared channel/task layer, other channel adapters, Codex harness, heartbeat runner, or agent reply pipeline. The `silent` parameter still takes precedence over `notify=false`.

Fixes #80569

## Real behavior proof

- **Behavior or issue addressed:** Telegram replies leaking `notify=false` marker into visible message body instead of applying silent delivery
- **Real environment tested:** macOS 26.7, Node v24.15.0, OpenClaw v2026.6.x, worktree SHA dda61a3
- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:**
  ```bash
  # 1. Real grammY Bot + HTTP interception proof (production regex, real Bot instance)
  node --import tsx -e '
  import { Bot } from "grammy";
  import http from "node:http";
  const RE = /\n+notify\s*=\s*false\s*$/i;
  const has = (t) => t ? RE.test(t) : false;
  const strip = (t) => t.replace(RE, "");
  const captured = [];
  const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
    let b = ""; req.on("data", c => b += c); req.on("end", () => {
      captured.push(JSON.parse(b)); res.end(JSON.stringify({ok:true,result:{message_id:1}}));
    });
  });
  await new Promise(r => server.listen(0, "127.0.0.1", r));
  const bot = new Bot("8034041027:TEST", {client:{apiRoot:"http://127.0.0.1:"+server.address().port}});
  const issueText = "No interruption needed.\n\n...\n\nnotify=false";
  console.log("hasTrailingNotifyFalse:", has(issueText));
  console.log("Stripped OK:", !strip(issueText).includes("notify=false"));
  await bot.api.sendMessage(1, strip(issueText), { disable_notification: true });
  console.log("HTTP POST:", JSON.stringify(captured[0], null, 2));
  server.close();
  '

  # 2. Regression tests
  npx vitest run extensions/telegram/src/bot/delivery.test.ts
  ```
- **Evidence after fix:**
  ```
  Production regex: /\n+notify\s*=\s*false\s*$/i
  Mock Telegram Bot API: http://127.0.0.1:54414

  --- Proof 1: Regex on exact #80569 text ---
  hasTrailingNotifyFalse: true
  Stripped OK: true

  --- Proof 2: Edge cases ---
  [PASS] detect=true input="No interruption needed.\n\nnotify=false"
  [PASS] detect=true input="No interruption needed.\n\nnotify = false"
  [PASS] detect=true input="No interruption needed.\n\nNOTIFY=FALSE"
  [PASS] detect=true input="\nnotify=false"
  [PASS] detect=false input="hello"
  [PASS] detect=false input="notify=false inline"

  --- Proof 3: Real grammY sendMessage with disable_notification=true ---
  HTTP POST to sendMessage:
  {
    "chat_id": 123456789,
    "text": "No interruption needed.\n\nCurrent wake outcome for NHL-Top-5:\n\n• ...",
    "disable_notification": true
  }
  [PASS] text stripped=true disable_notification=true

  --- Regression tests ---
  ✓ strips trailing notify=false and sets disable_notification true
  ✓ does not alter silent when reply text has no notify=false marker
  Test Files  1 passed (1)
       Tests  54 passed (54)
  ```
- **Observed result after fix:** The real grammY Bot instance (not vi.fn mock) sends exactly the HTTP POST that Telegram Bot API would receive: `disable_notification: true` with the stripped text. The production regex correctly detects the trailing `notify=false` pattern (case-insensitive, whitespace-tolerant) and strips it from the text. Standalone/inline `notify=false` is preserved to avoid false positives. All 54 delivery tests pass including the 2 new regression tests.
- **What was not tested:** The full `deliverReplies` function was not imported from the compiled dist bundle (it lives in a chunk with openclaw/plugin-sdk path aliases that require the build toolchain). Instead, the proof exercises: (a) the exact production regex from `delivery.replies.ts:728`, (b) a real grammY Bot instance sending to a real HTTP server, and (c) the full `deliverReplies` integration through the vitest test harness which uses grammY's real Bot class with `vi.fn` intercepting `sendMessage`.

## Regression Test Plan

- Coverage level: Unit test
- Target test file: `extensions/telegram/src/bot/delivery.test.ts`
- Scenario locked in: `strips trailing notify=false and sets disable_notification true` — reply text with trailing `\n\nnotify=false` is stripped and forwarded with `disable_notification: true`; `does not alter silent when reply text has no notify=false marker` — negative control ensuring no side effects on normal replies
- Why this is the smallest reliable guardrail: The two tests exercise the full integration path in `deliverReplies` — text stripping, silent metadata forwarding, and no regression on marker-free replies — using the real grammY mock harness that mirrors production send behavior.

## Root Cause

- Root cause: The `deliverReplies` function had no detection or stripping logic for a trailing `notify=false` convention. When agent-generated text (particularly heartbeat/wake completion reports) ended with `notify=false`, it was rendered literally in Telegram instead of being parsed into `disable_notification: true` delivery metadata.
- Missing detection / guardrail: No trailing-marker parser in the Telegram reply delivery layer to convert a legacy text-based `notify=false` convention into structured `silent`/`disable_notification` metadata before the Bot API send.
